data.content:
Here's the improved version using proper MSTest assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));  // All() is fine here—it's a LINQ predicate, not a weak assertion
    var admin = users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key changes:**

| Original | Replacement | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, ...)` | Redundant — the `== 3` check already covers it. If you just want "not empty", use `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` or `CollectionAssert.That.IsNotEmpty()` if available. |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)` | On failure, gives `Expected:<3> Actual:<5>` instead of `Expected:<True> Actual:<False>` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(admin)` | Clearer failure message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.All(...))` | *(kept as-is)* | `All()` is a LINQ predicate — this is a legitimate use of `Assert.IsTrue` |

**Other MSTest collection assertions to know:**

```csharp
// Verify contents
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);
CollectionAssert.DoesNotContain(users, bannedUser);

// Verify all elements match a type
CollectionAssert.AllArInstancesOfType(users, typeof(User));

// Verify exact equality (order matters)
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expectedList, users);

// Verify same elements (order ignored)
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expectedList, users);

// Verify no duplicates
CollectionAssert.AllAreUnique(users);

// Verify no nulls
CollectionAssert.AllAreNotNull(users);
```

**Rule of thumb:** if the assertion fails, would the message tell you *what went wrong*? If it only says `True != False`, use a more specific assertion.
